A dashboard is a visual representation of performance metrics and data related to a healthcare campaign. It provides an easy-to-understand overview of the campaign's performance and monitoring the campaign. The data presented on the dashboard is aggregated and anonymized, ensuring the confidentiality of individual households and population data.

The dashboard also enables analysis of the campaign's performance at various levels and provides visualizations such as graphs and heat maps. Using a dashboard can help health campaign platform users make informed decisions, improve the campaign's effectiveness, and ensure efficient delivery of healthcare services and interventions to the target population.

In any case, having a digital platform for managing and monitoring the healthcare campaign is essential for tracking progress and ensuring that the campaign's objectives are met.

In the healthcare campaign, Field Level Workers (FLWs) are responsible for collecting and inputting data related to households and citizens. This data is crucial in analyzing the performance of the campaign, identifying areas that require attention and monitoring progress.

The FLWs share this data while providing campaign services and interventions, enabling the system to collect relevant data at the ground level. The data collected by the FLWs is then used to create a comprehensive overview of the campaign's performance, which is presented on the campaign dashboard.

The healthcare campaign management service in the country is based on DIGIT, a platform that provides tools to manage healthcare campaigns effectively. This platform streamlines the process of data collection, storage, and analysis, making it easier for FLWs and boundary-level users to input data into the system. The platform also provides tools to generate reports and visualizations, making it easier to monitor the campaign's performance and identify areas for improvement.

Supervisors and warehouse managers, who are boundary-level users, also play a crucial role in providing datasets required for the dashboard. They contribute to the dashboard by providing data on the supply chain, stock management, and other relevant information. The datasets provided by these users are combined with the data collected by the FLWs to create a comprehensive picture of the healthcare campaign's performance.

The 'Number of days to last inventory' is a metric that represents the number of days the current inventory of bednets can last based on the current rate of consumption. This metric is useful for the dashboard users to determine when to order more bednets to ensure that there is an adequate supply to meet the demand.
The calculation involves the following steps:

Number of days the inventory can last based on the current consumption rate, this is calculated as the ‘total stock on hand’ divided by the total expected consumption for all warehouses within the boundary.
Determine the stock on hand as of today's date for each warehouse in the district or administrative post.

Calculate the total expected consumption for all warehouses within the boundary. This is calculated as the sum of the bed nets of the stock on hand for each warehouse and the daily microplan target for the district or administrative post.
Calculate the daily microplan target for bed nets.

It is important to note that the micro plan target should be set based on the daily bednet target for the province and the stock on hand should be considered for all warehouses within the boundary of the district or administrative post.

To calculate this metric, the application uses the inventory management data from the 'Stock Reconciliation' page, which includes the stock on hand for each warehouse individually. The calculation takes into account the daily microplan targets for bednets and the total number of warehouses within the boundary of the district or administrative post.

The "Stock in Hand” metric represents the total available and Required bednets as of today in each boundary according to the last updated data. This metric is calculated using the Inventory Management data from the Stock reconciliation page of the application, which includes the stock on hand for the current day. The calculation for the side-by-side bar graph is done as:

Calculate the number of ‘available’ bednets (Blue Bar): Get the stock in hand for the current day from the Inventory Management data. This includes the stock in hand day plus any stock received, minus any stock issued, returned on the current day. Further calculate the total available bed nets in each warehouse for the given boundary (District or Administrative Posts) by multiplying the daily micro plan target by the number of campaign days and summing across all warehouses.

Calculate the number of required bednets (Orange Bar): The bed nets required for the boundary as per the micro plan for the entire campaign duration based on the project setup. Further now calculate the cumulative bed nets distributed so far. Calculate the remaining bed nets required by subtracting the cumulative bed nets distributed from the bed nets required.

The resulting metric is represented as a side-by-side bar chart that shows the number of ‘available’ bednets and the actual ‘required’ number of bednets for each boundary. The "Available" bars are represented in blue, and the "Required" bars are represented in orange. The metric is presented in a default view of district-wise for national and provincial users and administrative-post wise for district-level users.

At the District role level, the calculation is the sum of households visited for each administrative province within the boundary for the selected date range.
At the National and Provincial role level, the calculation is the sum of households visited for each district within the boundary for the selected date range.

Overall, the Household Coverage Ranking will provide useful information for program managers to monitor which area (district / APs) have covered nearly all the household and where there is most pending, for the intervention coverage so that areas improvement / focus in the process can be planned.

The data required for the calculation will be obtained from the project setup and the application. The household coverage will be calculated based on the households visited which will be taken from the data submitted by the application. The household microplan target will be taken from the project setup.

The Household Coverage Ranking is in percentage and provides a visual representation of the performance of different districts or administrative posts in terms of achieving household coverage targets. The chart will be displayed as a bar chart in descending order from left to right.

For the national level role, the ranking will be provided for all the districts within the selected province. For the provincial level role, the ranking will be provided for all the districts within the respective province. For the district level role, the ranking will be provided for all the administrative posts within the respective district.

The calculation will be based on the ratio of the total households visited till today to the household microplan target for each district or administrative post. The result will be expressed as a percentage.
Number Of Days To Last Inventory

It is important to note that when calculating the total number of bed nets needed per day, the micro plan target should be based on the daily bed nets target for the province for national and provincial level users, and the district for district level users. Additionally, the sum total of "stock in hand" across all warehouses should be considered when calculating the number of days the inventory can last.
The number of days the inventory can last is then obtained by dividing the total stock in hand by the total number of bed nets needed per day.

The "Number Of Days To Last Inventory" is a bar chart that measures and displays how long the current inventory of bed nets can last based on the current rate of consumption. The metric is calculated by dividing the total number of bed nets in stock for all the warehouses for the boundary by the average daily consumption rate.
Overall, this metric provides an indication of the adequacy of bed net stocks and the need for replenishment to ensure that there are enough bed nets to meet the demand for campaign fulfillment.

The calculation for this metric involves obtaining the current "stock in hand" for each warehouse within the selected district, as obtained from the stock reconciliation page in the inventory management system. The daily bed nets microplan target is then obtained from the project setup data, and the total number of bed nets needed is calculated as the product of the daily target and the total number of warehouses in the district.

The bar chart will display the number of days the current inventory can last for each district within the selected province for national and provincial level users, and for each administrative post within the respective district for district level users.
The completion rate is then calculated as a percentage by dividing the Mandated Checklist completion rate by the Actual Checklist completion rate and multiplying the result by 100.

The ‘Actual National/Provincial/District Checklist completion rate’ is calculated by summing up the actual number of times each checklist was filled out by the respective supervisors within the selected date range.

The Overall Checklists Completion Rate bar chart displays the percentage of supervisors who have completed all the assigned checklists within a selected date range. The chart is divided into three categories: National, Provincial, and District supervisors.

The bar chart displays the completion rate of checklists for each boundary level (national, provincial, and district), based on the number of checklists assigned and the number of times they were actually completed by the supervisors.

For National and Provincial Supervisors, the ‘Mandated National/Provincial Checklist completion rate’ is calculated by multiplying the total number of national/provincial supervisors by the sum of the frequency of each checklist for the respective supervisor level. The Mandated District Checklist completion rate is calculated by multiplying the total number of district supervisors by the sum of the frequency of each checklist for the district level.

The calculation for the completion rate is based on the number of checklists that are mandated for each supervisor level and the actual number of times each checklist was filled out by supervisors within the selected date range.

This metric measures the percentage of the population that has been covered with the intervention (in this case, the distribution of bed nets) against the microplan target. The microplan target refers to the number of individuals that were targeted to receive the intervention according to the project setup.

Additionally, an insight is available to show the percentage change in population coverage from the previous day. This can provide an indication of how quickly the population coverage is increasing or decreasing compared to the previous day.

The calculation takes the sum of the population covered (based on the quantity of bed nets distributed) for the selected province, district, or corresponding district (depending on the user role) since the start of the campaign, and then divides it by the population microplan target for that area. This quotient is then multiplied by 100 to get a percentage.

In other words, we are calculating the total population covered for the selected date range by summing up the population covered for each household within the selected boundary. The boundary data is obtained from MDMS.
In the "Population Covered" metric, firstly, we need to know the population data of the household, which can be found in the "Delivery Intervention" screen and let us denote it as "b".

For the selected date range, we need to sum up the "a" values for all households within the selected boundary (districts for national and provincial level roles, and Administrative Post for district level roles).
Then, we calculate the “population covered” for each household by multiplying "b" by 1.8, which is denoted as "a".
In summary, the "Population Targeted" metric gives an indication of the expected coverage or reach of the campaign, and can help to assess the campaign towards achieving its goals.

The "Population Targeted" metric refers to the total number of people that are expected to be reached or covered by the campaign during the selected date range. This metric is based on the microplan targets that were set up during the project setup phase.

To calculate the population target for the date range, the microplan targets for the province or district are multiplied by the number of days in the selected date range. This gives an estimate of the total number of people that are expected to be reached or covered during the campaign. The boundary data used for this calculation is obtained from MDMS.

The population target varies based on the user role. For the national level role and provincial level role, the population target is for the selected “province”, while for the district level role, it is for the “Administrative Posts”.
This indicates the percentage of field workers who have synced their device at least once for the current day, i.e. from 12:00AM to 11:59PM.
Overall, this metric provides an indication of the progress of the campaign in distributing bed nets to the targeted population.

This metric represents the total number of bed nets distributed since the start of the campaign, for the selected province, corresponding province, or corresponding district.
This formula is applied for the entire campaign duration, which is calculated as the time between the campaign start date and the current date.

To calculate this metric, the quantity of bed nets distributed to households is captured in the "Delivery Intervention" screen of the application and recorded in the "Quantity distributed" field. The start date of the campaign is determined during the project setup phase, and the boundary data is obtained from the MDMS.

This metric measures the total number of households visited since the start of the campaign. It is calculated by aggregating all the households visited for the selected province or district since the start of the campaign, depending on the user’s role level. The input fields for this metric include the households visited data which is collected by the Field worker application, the campaign start date from the Campaign project setup, and boundary data from MDMS.
This also provides additional insights into the percentage change in the number of households visited from the previous day to today.
Overall, the Total Population Covered (Cumulative) metric provides an indication of how effective the intervention has been in reaching the target population and meeting the campaign goals.

The Total Population Covered (Cumulative) is a metric that shows the total population covered since the start of the campaign, and it is used for monitoring the progress of the intervention in reaching the target population. This metric is applicable for all user roles: national, provincial, and district level, the data will be displayed as per the boundaries permission allotted.

Additionally, an insight is available for this metric, which is (Today - Previous day) / Previous Day * 100. This insight shows the percentage increase or decrease in the metric from the previous day to the current day.

To calculate this metric, we use the Population Data for household Covered, which is obtained by multiplying the Quantity of bednets Distributed to the household by 1.8. The campaign start date is obtained from the Project Setup, and the Boundary data is obtained from the MDMS.

It's important to note that if a field worker has synced their data once but after that it has unsynced data, it will not be reflected in this KPI.

The Bed nets Distributed KPI shows a bar chart with the total number of bed nets distributed within a selected date range and boundary. The data is collected from the Delivery Intervention Screen in the mobile application, specifically the Quantity distributed field.

Planned vs Actual Campaign Progress (Bed nets)

The Planned vs Actual Campaign Progression (Bednets) chart displays the comparison of bed nets distributed, showing the planned and actual distribution over time. The chart also extrapolates the graph to show when the bed nets distribution will meet the target. The data for bed nets distributed is taken from the Delivery Intervention Screen's 'Quantity distributed' field, and the target bed nets from the Micro plan.

For the planned line, the cumulative 'Quantity distributed' for the assigned boundary is used, and for the actual line, the 'Quantity distributed' for the date range is used. To calculate the X-intercept, the bed nets targeted to distribute per day for assigned boundary or district is multiplied by the number of days in the date range (Campaign start date - TODAY). Finally, the interval for the x-axis is kept for every 1 day.
The interval for the X-axis is kept for every 1 day, meaning that each point on the chart represents the progress made in one day.

To calculate the X-intercept of the “planned” line, the number of households targeted to visit per day for the assigned boundary is multiplied by the number of days in the date range (Campaign start date - TODAY). For the X-intercept of the “actual” line, the current date is added to the difference between the target number of households and the total number of households visited to date, divided by the number of households targeted per day.

This chart is used to track the planned versus actual progress of a campaign to deliver household visits, and to project when the campaign will reach its target. The chart is a line chart with two lines: one for the planned progress and one for the actual progress.

The “actual” line represents the actual number of households that were visited each day, starting from the beginning of the campaign up to the current day. The total number of households visited for each day is used to plot this line. The X-intercept of the actual line shows the projected date when the campaign is expected to meet its target, based on the current rate of progress.

The “planned” line represents the expected number of households that should have been visited each day, based on the micro plan. The cumulative number of households that were targeted to visit each day is used to plot this line. The X-intercept of the planned line shows the date when the campaign is expected to meet its target.
The x-axis interval is set to 1 day, meaning that each point on the chart represents the progress made in one day.

The calculation of the intercept is done by dividing the difference between the target population and the actual population covered by the population targeted per day and adding the result to today's date.
This is a line chart that compares the planned and actual campaign progression for population coverage.

The actual data is obtained from the quantity distributed for a given date range. The X-intercept on the chart indicates when the population target is expected to be met based on the current rate of coverage.
Planned data is calculated by adding up the cumulative quantity delivered and multiplying it by a factor of 1.8, representing the average population per household.

This KPI visualization in the “Registration and Delivery” dashboard section displays the total population covered within the selected date range. For the "%" toggle, the data is presented as a percentage of the total population covered, calculated by summing the number of individuals covered in each household and multiplying it by 100, and then dividing it by the daily population microplan target and the number of days in the selected date range. The data is presented separately for each boundary, which could be districts for national and provincial roles, and Administrative posts for district roles.

For the "Number" toggle, the data is presented as a sum of all households visited within the selected date range. The data is presented separately for each boundary, which could be districts for national and provincial roles, and Administrative posts for district roles.

The report allows for drill-down functionality, allowing users to view data at a more granular level for each boundary. The Target Achievement columns show the percentage of micro plan targets achieved for household coverage, population coverage, and bed nets distribution.

District Level User: He is able to view the data for the respective district that he has been assigned.

The formula used to calculate the coverage percentage is the sum of the bed nets distributed in each AP divided by the bed nets micro plan target for that AP.

The heat map metric measures the distribution coverage of bed nets achieved against micro plan targets across different districts. The micro plan targets are set up during the project setup phase, and the bed nets distributed are recorded in the Delivery Intervention screen in the mobile application under the Quantity Distributed field.

For district-level users, the default view of the heat map is at the assigned district level, with the bed nets distribution coverage indicated as a percentage for each administrative post (AP) within the district. However, since shapefiles are not available at the AP level, the view will have only the district outer boundary and not AP boundaries within it.

For national and provincial level users, the default view of the heat map is at the province level, with the bed nets distribution coverage indicated as a percentage for each district. The formula used to calculate the coverage percentage is the sum of the bed nets distributed in each district divided by the bed nets micro plan target for that district.

Finally, due to the unavailability of shapefiles beyond the district level, zooming in beyond the district level is not possible, and therefore, the map will only show the outer boundary of the district or administrative post.
The metric also provides an insight that compares the household coverage between two days, expressed as a percentage change.

The Target Achievement of Households shows the geo map with percentage of households covered against the micro plan targets set for a particular district or administrative post. The micro plan targets are set at the project setup stage, and the household coverage is based on data fetched from the mobile application, which shows the households that have been visited. The metric is presented as a heat map that visualizes the percentage of household coverage achieved across different districts.

For district-level users, the default view of the map is at the district level, and the metric is calculated as follows: Total households visited till today in an administrative post (AP) divided by the Household Micro plan target set for that AP multiplied by 100. The same calculation is performed for each AP within the district.

For national and provincial users, the default view of the map is at the province level, and the metric is calculated as follows: Total households visited till today in a district divided by the Household Micro plan target set for that district multiplied by 100. The same calculation is performed for each district within the province.
Insights will be available in terms of percentage change in coverage between today and the previous day.
However, due to the unavailability of shapefiles beyond the district level, there will be no zoom-in available for both national/provincial and district-level users.
This metric measures the population coverage achieved against the micro plan targets in percentage. It will be presented as a heat map that shows the coverage percentage across different districts.

For national and provincial level users, the default view will be at the province level, with the coverage percentage calculated as the sum of the population data covered in each district divided by the population micro plan target of that district, multiplied by 100. The same formula will be used for district-level users, with the default view set at the district level.

The micro plan targets and boundary data are provided in the project setup, while the bed nets distributed and population data covered are obtained from the delivery intervention screen in the application. The population data covered is calculated as the quantity distributed multiplied by 1.8, which is the average number of people per household in the country.

This metric of the tabular chart displays the different boundaries for which the open complaints data count is reported. The boundary data will be as per the user role. The Summary Report for Open Complaints is a tabular chart that shows the overview of complaints that are open from a particular duration with respect to the boundary. The report is categorized according to different boundaries within MDMS, and the complaints data is sourced for the “Open”, Complaints data module in the mobile application. The report allows for drill-down capabilities from one level of boundary to the last.

This report shows the total number of open complaints for a particular boundary where the complaints have been open for more than 48 hours during the selected date range. The report calculates this by summing all the complaints where the status is "Open" and the time between the created time and 23:59 hours on selected end Date is more than 48 hours.

The total number of open complaints is calculated by subtracting the sum of rejected and resolved complaints from the total number of complaints. The boundary for users can be a district for National & Provincial supervisors, and Administrative post for District supervisors. The last row of the column should be the sum of all columns above, which represents the total number of open complaints for more than 48 hours in the selected date range.

The "Open since < 6 Hours" summary report shows the total number of open complaints that are less than 6 hours old for the selected date range. The calculation for this report involves summing up all complaints where the status is "Open" and the complaint was created within the selected date range. In addition to this, the complaint must also have been created within 6 hours of the end of the selected date range.
The last row of the column shows the total sum of all columns above. This report helps supervisors to quickly identify newly registered complaints that need to be addressed urgently.

The "Open since > 6 hrs & <12 hrs" column in the summary report shows the total number of open complaints for the selected date range that have been open for more than 6 hours but less than 12 hours. The calculation is based on the time difference between the created time of the complaint and the end of the day on the specified date, which should fall between 6 and 12 hours.

The total number of open complaints for a given boundary (i.e., district or province) is calculated by summing all the complaints in that boundary that have the "OPEN" status and were created within the selected date range. This number is then further filtered to include only those complaints that have been open for more than 6 hours but less than 12 hours. The last row of the column shows the sum of all the values in that column for each boundary.

The "Open since > 12 hours & <24 hours" section of the report shows the total number of open complaints that have been open for more than 12 hours but less than 24 hours, for a particular boundary within the selected date range. This is calculated by adding up all the complaints with the status of "OPEN" that were created within the boundary and have been open for more than 12 hours but less than 24 hours.

The open complaints are determined by subtracting the sum of "Resolved" and "Rejected” complaints from the total complaints created for the boundary. The boundary is for which the data is being displayed, which can be District or Provincial, depending on the user role assigned. The last row of the column shows the sum of all the complaints in the column.

This report shows the total number of complaints that are still open and have not been resolved within the specified time frame, which is between 24 to 48 hours. The calculation is based on the time difference between the complaint creation time and the end of the day on the selected date. The data is filtered by the boundary of districts for national and provincial supervisors, and Administrative Posts for district supervisors.

The open complaints are calculated as the difference between the total complaints and the resolved and rejected complaints. The last row of the column is the sum of all the values in the respective columns. This report helps supervisors to monitor the number of open complaints that have not been resolved within the specified time frame.

If a date range is selected, the end date will default to today's date. The report will display the total number of open complaints for each boundary, with the last row of the column showing the sum of all columns. In summary, the Summary Report for Open Complaints provides a quick overview of the number of complaints that are still open within a selected duration and allows users to drill down to different levels of boundaries to get more granular information.

This metric of the tabular chart displays the different boundaries for which the complaints data is reported. The boundary data will be as per the user role. I.e. ‘National’ and ‘provincial’ level users will get district level boundary data, whereas ‘district’ level users will get administrative post level boundary data. The drill-down functionality will be available for all levels of boundaries.

The summary report for total complaints will be presented in a tabular chart format, which will provide an overview of the total complaints according to the boundary. Each boundary will be clickable and will allow drilling down to the next level of boundary for detailed information. The boundary data will be taken from the MDMS, and complaints data will be from the complaints module in the mobile application.

The ‘Open’ Complaints in the summary report refers to the total number of complaints that are currently open and have not yet been resolved or rejected. All the complaints which do not have the status as Resolved or Rejected are termed as open; else to whatever state/status they are in. This means that no action has been taken on these complaints, and they are still waiting for attention from the relevant authorities.

Finally, the report provides a total row at the bottom that sums up all the open complaints for all the boundaries. This information is helpful in identifying the workload and the current state of the complaint handling process.

The report calculates this number by summing up all the complaints in the selected boundary where the status is marked as "Open" and the date range is within the selected range. The report distinguishes between the different levels of authorities, such as National, Provincial, or District supervisors, and shows the total number of open complaints for each one accordingly.

This provides information about the total number of complaints registered for the selected date range for each boundary level. The calculation for the "Total Complaints Registered" is the sum of all complaints that were created for the selected date range for each boundary level.

This includes complaints that are open, resolved, and rejected. The last row of the column should be equal to the sum of all the columns above it, providing the total number of complaints registered across all boundary levels.

This the total number of complaints that were rejected by a supervisor for the selected date range. The data field in the report shows the total number of complaints rejected for each boundary. Further the boundaries displayed depend on the user role, with national and provincial level users seeing districts as the default boundary data, while district level users see administrative posts as the default boundary data.
The last row of the "Rejected by Supervisor" column shows the sum of all columns above it, indicating the total number of complaints rejected for all boundaries.

The drill-down feature is available for all boundaries, till the last village level. To calculate the total number of complaints rejected for each boundary, the system sums up all the complaints where the status is marked as "Rejected" and where the boundary is equal to different districts or administrative posts as applicable by user role and the date range is the one selected by the user.

The purpose of the section is to show the total number of complaints that were resolved within the selected date range for each boundary. This displays the data for each boundary, which could be district or administrative posts depending on the user's role. The calculation for the number of resolved complaints involves adding up all the complaints where the status is marked as "RESOLVED" for a given boundary and date range.
The last row of the "Resolved" column shows the sum of all the resolved complaints for each boundary, giving an overall count of the number of complaints resolved for the selected date range.

The "Date" column in the summary report with "Day" toggle shows the complaint data according to the date. The default view is the starting date of the campaign. and there is no drill-down available for the dates.

The Summary Report with 'Day' Toggle displays a tabular chart that shows data for each day of the campaign, with no drill down on the dates. The report shows Complaint data as per the date, with Boundary data coming from MDMS and Complaint data from the Complaints module in the mobile application. The last row of each column will be the total sum of all columns. The Date Report does not have any change as per the date range selected. The Report will be from the Campaign start date till today.

The "Open" column in the Day toggle chart shows the total number of complaints on a particular day for which no action has been taken yet and the status is not Rejected or Resolved. Using the three metrics (Total Complaints: / Rejected / Resolved), the number of open complaints can be calculated by subtracting the total number of resolved and rejected complaints from the total number of complaints created on a particular day.
The last row of the column shows the sum of all open complaints. The Day toggle chart data is not affected by the date range selection.

The summary of Registered complaints shows the total number of complaints that have been registered on each day. The total complaints registered for a particular date is calculated by summing up all the complaints that have been created on that date for the user boundary allotted. The boundary data is determined by the user's role.

National and provincial supervisors will have the default boundary data set to the district, whereas district supervisors will have administrative posts as the default boundary data. The total number of complaints is calculated as the sum of all complaints that are currently open, resolved, or rejected.

The "Rejected by Supervisor" column in the Day toggle chart displays the total number of complaints that were rejected by the supervisor for each date. This is calculated as the difference between "Total Complaints Registered" and the sum of open and resolved complaints.

The last row of the column shows the total number of complaints that were rejected by the supervisor, across all dates. It should be noted that the Day toggle chart is not affected by the date range selection, and always displays data for each day of the campaign.

This section in the summary report for ‘Day’ toggle shows the total number of complaints that were resolved on each date. This is calculated by summing up all the complaints that have a status of "RESOLVED" for the corresponding date and boundary (i.e., "Province" for Provincial and National supervisors and "District" for District supervisors).

The last row of the "Resolved" column is the sum of all the resolved complaints for all the dates. The Day toggle chart is not affected by the DATE RANGE selection, which means that the chart will show data for each day of the campaign regardless of the selected date range.

For ‘national/provincial supervisors’, the number of entries is calculated where supervisor level is national and checklists are the different checklists available to be filled. For ‘district supervisors’, the number of entries is calculated where supervisor level is national and checklists are different checklists available to be filled at the district level.

To calculate this metric, the application requires input fields such as the level of supervisor, frequency of checklist completion, and the number of checklists created within the selected/assigned province or district and selected date range.

The level of the supervisor is obtained from the user management module, and the frequency of checklist completion is also considered in the calculation. For national/provincial supervisors, the number of entries is calculated for the selected/assigned province and the checklist name, whereas for district supervisors, the number of entries is calculated for the assigned district and checklist name.
The data required for the calculation of this metric is obtained from the supervisor application/module, which is used for checklists completion.

Provincial Supervisors Checklists Completion Rate is a metric that shows the percentage completion of checklists by provincial-level supervisors. This bar chart is displayed in the dashboard, and helps to monitor the performance of the checklist that has been filled and submitted by provincial-level supervisors.
This calculation is performed for each checklist assigned to the provincial-level supervisors, and the results are displayed in a bar chart format.

To calculate this metric, the number of checklists created for provincial-level supervisors to be filled, for the selected/assigned province and selected date range is counted, and the number of checklists completed is calculated. The completed checklists are then divided by the total number of checklists created, and this ratio is multiplied by 100 to get the percentage completion rate.

The ‘Supervisor’ section in the dashboard provides a visual representation of the actions taken by supervisors on the activities / checklist assigned to them. This section shows the response of all three levels of users: National, Provincial, and District.
This information can be used by higher-level management to monitor the progress of activities and identify any potential issues that may arise.

At the National level, the dashboard displays the number of times the checklist has been allotted and filled by the supervisors across the country. At the Provincial level, the dashboard shows the same information but only for the province in question. At the District level, the dashboard displays the number of times the checklist has been allotted and filled by the supervisors for the district.

Here are the steps to download or share the dashboard:
In the Data Sync card, there is a metric called "sync rate" that indicates the percentage of total workers who have synced their device at least once for the day.
The sync rate shows the proportion of data collected by all workers that have been synced with the system, indicating the dashboard's data is up-to-date.
At the top of the screen, they will see the "Bed Nets Distributed" card.
The "Total household visited" data on the Household card represents the total number of households visited since the start of the campaign across all provinces.
In this card, the "Total Bednet Distributed" metric displays the total number of bednets that have been distributed since the beginning of the campaign across all provinces.
The "Total user created" count on this card represents the total number of workers assigned to the selected campaign.
To download the entire page, click on the "Download" button located at the top right corner of the page.

To download or share an individual card, graph, or summary table, click on the kebab menu icon (a vertical three dots icon) located at the top right corner of each individual card, and choose the download or share option.

To drill down to various boundary levels of data in the dashboard, users can click on the legends with the different boundary names displayed on the "bar graph," "heat map," and "summary reports." For instance, if a user wants to view data at a lower level, they can click on the name of the boundary to scatter it to the next lowest level of data.
To share the entire page, click on the "Share" button at the top right corner of the page and choose the desired sharing option (such as WhatsApp or email).

This means that the user can easily navigate through different levels of data, from higher administrative levels such as provinces and districts, to lower administrative levels such as localities and villages.
The user will be directed to the national dashboard for the selected campaign.

To view and compare the household coverage ranking for boundary data, users can access the overview section of the province-level dashboard for National and Province Level Users, or the District Level dashboard for District Level Users. The bar graph is available in the “Household Coverage Ranking” Card in this section which arranges boundaries in descending order based on their household coverage data, making it easy for users to compare rankings.
